Airbnb is one of the most famous online marketplace that allows users to accommodate guests with short-term lodging and tourism-related activities all over the world. The company was founded in August 2008 by Brian Chesky, Nathan Blecharczyk and Joe Gebbia in San Francisco, CA. The idea was born by the difficulties of Chesky and Gebbia, at this time students in San Francisco, to pay the house rent. This situation bring them to put an air mattress in their living room and turning it into a bed and breakfast to "make a few bucks".

Over time the company has evolved and has reached 1 billion dollar of revenue in the third quarter of 2018.

The company offers several different packets beyond its core component such as experiences, Airbnb Plus, Airbnb Collections, Niido and Natiivo.

In the proposed work we perfomed an analysis of the Airbnb market since november 2018 in city of Berlin which is one of the most attractive city in Europe. The work is divided in four core parts. We firstly performed an analysis of the dataset in order to understand its structure and some important aspects of the AirBnb market in the city, after this the unsupervised method PCA for dimensionality reduction is performed. Then, we moved to supervised methods by providing several classifiers which, given some features like the district, the price etc., have to predict the correspondent type of room. Lastly a some regressors are used to predict the price of the accomodation given the other features.

The Berlin Airbnb dataset is made available by Airbnb at the following URL: http://insideairbnb.com/get-the-data.html

The analyzed datased is the one referring to 07 November 2018 as compiled date. More recent data are also available.

We will remove all the columns not useful for supervised and unsupervised techniques such as the host name, host id, latitude, logitude etc. Moreover we replace all the rows that contains a NaN with the column average value. The cleaned dataset contains the following columns:

2.2 Data standardize ¶

In a context of multivariate analysis it is proved how the stardize operation must be done before applying any supervised or unsupervised technique, otherwise variable measured at different scales do not contribute equally to the analysis. In fact a variable that ranges between 0 and 500 will totally outweight another variable that ranges between 0 and 1. The aim of the standardize operation is to transform all the data in a comparable scale.

Tha standardize operation for a given column $\textbf{X}_k$ is the following:

$\textbf{X}_{k,std} = \frac{\textbf{X}_k - \overline{X}_k}{\sigma}$

Where $\overline{X}_k$ is the mean of the column $\textbf{X}_k$ and $\sigma$ its standard deviation. Before doing the standardization we prepare the dataset for the classification and for the regression by dividing it in two different dataset. The one for the classification have as target the room type, the one for the regression has as target the price.

In [0]:
#preparing for regression
y_regr = berlin_cleaned['price'] #target
x_regr = berlin_cleaned.drop(columns='price') #features

x_class = berlin_cleaned.drop(columns='room_type') #features

#remove the categorical data before make standardize
rooms_t = berlin_cleaned['room_type']  
districts = berlin_cleaned['neighbourhood_group']
x_regr = x_regr.drop(columns='room_type')
x_regr = x_regr.drop(columns='neighbourhood_group')

#standardize the data
x_regr = (x_regr - x_regr.mean()) / x_regr.std()
#x_regr = StandardScaler().fit_transform(x_regr) #boring, returns a numpy.ndarray (re-build the dataframe)

x_class = (x_class - x_class.mean()) / x_class.std()
#x_class = StandardScaler().fit_transform(x_class) #boring, returns a numpy.ndarray (re-build the dataframe)

#avoid too little values
x_regr[abs(x_regr) < 1e-12] = 0
x_class[abs(x_class) < 1e-12] = 0

#avoid infinite values
x_regr.replace(np.inf, np.finfo(np.float64).max)
x_class.replace(-np.inf, -np.finfo(np.float64).max)

#add the categorical columns
x_regr['room_type'] = rooms_t
x_regr['neighbourhood_group'] = districts
x_class['neighbourhood_group'] = districts

2.3 PCA ¶

Principal component analysis (PCA) is an unsupervised technique used for dimensionality reduction for pre-processing before supervised methods and for data visualization. The dataset after the cleaning phase contains 7 different columns, if we want to represents them on a 2D scatter-plot we need to plot them 2 by 2, for an overall of $\frac{7*(7-1)}{2} = 21$ different plots.

In general if we have a matrix with $\textit{p}$ columns corresponding to $\textit{X}_1, \textit{X}_2, ..., \textit{X}_p$ features and $\textit{n}$ different rows corresponding to the observations, we need $\frac{p*(p-1)}{2}$ different subplots in order to visualize features 2 by 2. The analysis become not feasible as $\textit{p}$ increases.

PCA aims to find a low-dimensional representation of a dataset that contains as much information as possible (variance). It is based on the idea that not all the subspaces are equally interesting and so some of them can be discarded or combined together.

Each of the dimension of PCA is a linear combination of the $\textit{p}$ features. The first PC of a set of features $\textit{X}_1, \textit{X}_2, ..., \textit{X}_p$ is the normalized linear combination of the features:

$Z_1 = \phi_{11}X_1+\phi_{21}X_2+\phi_{31}X_3+...+\phi_{1p}X_p$, subject to $\sum_{j=1}^{p} \phi_{j1}^2=1$

where $\phi_1 = (\phi_{11} \phi_{21} \phi_{31} ... \phi_{p1})^T$ are the loadings which represents the direction on which the features are projected. These loading are choosen in a way that they defines a direction in the feature space along which the data vary the most. The loadings can be found by solving the following optimization problem:

$ \phi_1 = (\phi_{11} \phi_{21} \dots \phi_{p1}) : \textit{maximize} \frac{1}{n} \sum_{i=1}^{n}(\sum_{j=1}^{p}\phi_{j1}x_{ij})^2$, subject to $\sum_{j=1}^{p} \phi_{j1}^2=1$

This optimization problem can be solved both by Singular Value Decomposition (SVD) or eigenvectors extraction as we will see.

The second PC is the linear combination of $\textit{X}_1, \textit{X}_2, ..., \textit{X}_p$ that has the maximal variance among all linear combinations that are uncorrelated with $\textit{Z}_1$. Can be proved that $\textit{Z}_2$ is uncorrelated with $\textit{Z}_2$ when $\phi_2$ is orthogonal to $\phi_1$.

So at the end PCA means to find a matrix $\Phi$ such that:

$\begin{bmatrix} \phi_{11} & \phi_{12} & \phi_{13} & \dots & \phi_{1k} & \dots & \phi_{1m} \\ \phi_{21} & \phi_{22} & \phi_{23} & \dots & \phi_{2k} & \dots & \phi_{2m} \\ \dots & \dots & \dots & \dots & \dots & \dots & \dots \\ \phi_{p1} & \phi_{p2} & \phi_{p3} & \dots & \phi_{pk} & \dots & \phi_{pm} \end{bmatrix}$

where each column is the loading of a PC and all of them must be orthogonal and normal, which means that we need to find an orthonormal basis for the matrix $\textbf{X} \epsilon \mathbb{R}^{nxp}$ and so the principal component directions (the columns) $\phi_{1} \phi_{2} \phi_{3} ... \phi_{m}$ are the ordered sequence of eigenvectors of the matrix $\textbf{X}^T\textbf{X}$ and the variances of each components corresponds with its eigenvalue. There are at most $\textit{min(n-1, p)}$ principal components.

The principal components are unique except for a sign flip because since the PCs contains information about directions, the direction will be the same if the sign is changing, moreover $\textit{var(Z) = var(-Z)}$. This means that different software packages end up with the same PCs.

PCA using eigenvalues¶

  • standardize the matrix
  • compute the covariance matrix
  • compute eigenvectors and sort them in descending order based on the value of the correspondent eigenvalue
  • select the first k components

PCA using SVD¶

With the singular value decomposition of the matrix $\textbf{X}$ we obtain:

$\textbf{X} = \textbf{U} \textbf{S} \textbf{V}^T $

where

  • the columns of $\textbf{U}$ represents the eigenvectors $\{\phi_1, \dots, \phi_m\}$ and can be used to reconstruct the data using linear combinations of the eigenvectors
  • the matrix $\textbf{S}$ is diagonal and shows the importance of each eigenvector
  • the columns of $\textbf{V}^T$ contains the coefficients for reconstructing the samples

How many PCs to choose?¶

In order to understand how many PCs its better to have we need to analyze the quantity of variance (information) each components carries with it. We are interested in knowing the Proportion of Variance Explained (PVE). By defining the total variance of the normalized (zero mean) dataset as:

$\sum_{j=1}^{p}Var(X_j) = \frac{1}{n}\sum_{j=1}^{p}\sum_{i=1}^{n}x_{ij}^2$

and the variance expressed by the m-th components as:

$\frac{1}{n}\sum_{i=1}^{n}z_{im}^2 = \frac{1}{n}\sum_{i=1}^{n}\sum_{j=1}^{p}(\phi_{jm}x_{ij})^2$

Therefore the PVE expressed by the m-th component is equal to

$\frac{\frac{1}{n}\sum_{i=1}^{n}\sum_{j=1}^{p}(\phi_{jm}x_{ij})^2}{\frac{1}{n}\sum_{j=1}^{p}\sum_{i=1}^{n}x_{ij}^2}$

The PVE is a positive number between 0 and 1. In order to compute the PVE expressed by the first $\textit{M}$ components we can just sum the PVE of each of them.

Here we analyze the number of useful PCs by displaying the PEV.

#Define the functions used to plot the learning curve later
# partially based on https://scikit-learn.org/stable/auto_examples/model_selection/plot_learning_curve.html
def plot_learning_curve(estimator, title, X, y, cv=None, n_jobs=-1, train_sizes=np.linspace(.1, 1.0, 5)):
    """
    Generate a simple plot of the test and training learning curve.

    Parameters
    ----------
    estimator : object type that implements the "fit" and "predict" methods
        An object of that type which is cloned for each validation.

    title : string
        Title for the chart.

    X : array-like, shape (n_samples, n_features)
        Training vector, where n_samples is the number of samples and
        n_features is the number of features.

    y : array-like, shape (n_samples) or (n_samples, n_features), optional
        Target relative to X for classification or regression;
        None for unsupervised learning.

    cv : int, cross-validation generator or an iterable, optional
        Determines the cross-validation splitting strategy.
        Possible inputs for cv are:
          - None, to use the default 3-fold cross-validation,
          - integer, to specify the number of folds.
          - :term:`CV splitter`,
          - An iterable yielding (train, test) splits as arrays of indices.

        For integer/None inputs, if ``y`` is binary or multiclass,
        :class:`StratifiedKFold` used. If the estimator is not a classifier
        or if ``y`` is neither binary nor multiclass, :class:`KFold` is used.

        Refer :ref:`User Guide <cross_validation>` for the various
        cross-validators that can be used here.

    n_jobs : int or None, optional (default=None)
        Number of jobs to run in parallel.
        ``None`` means 1 unless in a :obj:`joblib.parallel_backend` context.
        ``-1`` means using all processors. See :term:`Glossary <n_jobs>`
        for more details.

    train_sizes : array-like, shape (n_ticks,), dtype float or int
        Relative or absolute numbers of training examples that will be used to
        generate the learning curve. If the dtype is float, it is regarded as a
        fraction of the maximum size of the training set (that is determined
        by the selected validation method), i.e. it has to be within (0, 1].
        Otherwise it is interpreted as absolute sizes of the training sets.
        Note that for classification the number of samples usually have to
        be big enough to contain at least one sample from each class.
        (default: np.linspace(0.1, 1.0, 5))
    """
    
    train_sizes, train_scores, test_scores = learning_curve(
        estimator, X, y, cv=cv, n_jobs=n_jobs, train_sizes=train_sizes)
    train_scores_mean = np.mean(train_scores, axis=1)
    train_scores_std = np.std(train_scores, axis=1)
    test_scores_mean = np.mean(test_scores, axis=1)
    test_scores_std = np.std(test_scores, axis=1)
    
    plt.figure(figsize=(12,6))
    plt.fill_between(train_sizes, train_scores_mean - train_scores_std,
                     train_scores_mean + train_scores_std, alpha=0.1,
                     color="r")
    plt.fill_between(train_sizes, test_scores_mean - test_scores_std,
                     test_scores_mean + test_scores_std, alpha=0.1, color="g")
    plt.plot(train_sizes, train_scores_mean, 'o-', color="r",
             label="Training score")
    plt.plot(train_sizes, test_scores_mean, 'o-', color="g",
             label="Cross-validation score")
    plt.xlabel('#samples')
    plt.ylabel('Score')
    plt.title(title)
    plt.show()

3.1 SVM ¶

The goal of the support vector classifier (SVC) is to find the hyperplane that separates the classes in feature space.
First of all, we can consider the Maximal Margin Classifier:
the hyperplane to find is a flat affine subspace, for example in 2D, it is a flat one-dimensional subspace, i.e. a line, described by:

$\beta_0 + \beta_1 \cdot X_1 + \beta_2 \cdot X_2 = 0$

In general, for a p-dimensional space, we have:
$f(x) = \beta_0 + \beta_1 \cdot X_1 + \beta_2 \cdot X_2 + ... + \beta_p \cdot X_p = $
$ = \beta_0 + <\beta, X> = 0$

where $(\beta_0, \beta_1, ... , \beta_p)$ is called normal vector, that points in a direction orthogonal to the surface of a hyperplane.
So, we can consider:

  • $f(x) < 0$ if $y_i = -1$
  • $f(x) > 0$ if $y_i = 1$
  • $f(x) = 0$ defines the separating hyperplane and $y_i \cdot f(x) > 0, \forall i$.

The classifier aims to find, between all possible hyperplane, the one that maximizes the margin M between two classes:

$ maximize\:M \\ subject\:to \sum_{j=1}^{p} \beta_j^2 = 1 \\ and\,y_i \cdot f(x) \geqslant M, \forall i$

But, sometimes the data are noisy, although they are separable, leading to a bad result of Maximal Margin Classifier. Then, the SVC is used to maximize a soft margin. We can add a slack variable $\epsilon$ to consider the presence of noisy points:
$ maximize\:M \\ subject\:to \sum_{j=1}^{p} \beta_j^2 = 1 \\ and\,y_i \cdot f(x) \geqslant M\cdot (1-\epsilon_i),\\\epsilon_i \geqslant 0, \sum_{i=1}^{p}\epsilon_i \leqslant C, \forall i$

where C is a regularization parameter, that tells us like "how many data would you eventually consider in the area with the higest probability of error".
But, there are cases where the regularization is not enough, due to the distribution of samples.
In this cases, it's possible to colve this situation by enlarging the feature space by including transformations. Fitting the SVC on this space, we will have a non-linear decision boundaries in the original space.
To introduce the non-linearities in SVC, we can use kernels, due to the fact that it's verified the property that:
$K(x_i, x_j) = < x_i, x_j>$

We can define our linear support vector as:
$f(x) = \beta_0 + \sum_{i=1}^{p}\alpha_i \cdot < x, x_i> $.

To estimate the weights $\alpha_i$ and the bias term $\beta_0$, we need of all inner products between all pairs of training set.
Then, there will be $\alpha_i$ estimated, equal to 0. This means that, the only data that will matter, are the ones with $\alpha_i > 0$. They are the support vectors, in the sense that they "support" our classification, while all the others are useless. Overall, if we can compute the inner products between all observations, we can fit the SVC, by means of kernel functions, that perform the inner product in different dimensional spaces.
The decision function becomes:
$f(x) = \beta_0 + \sum_{i \in S}\alpha_i \cdot K(x,x_i)$

Note that the summation now is for $i \in S$ to consider only the support vector, S is the set of cases where $\alpha_i > 0$. Examples of kernel function:

  • Polynomial: $k(x_i,x_j) = (1 + \sum_{k=1}^{p}x_{ik} \cdot x_{jk})^2$
  • RBF (Radial Basis Function) = $k(x_i,x_j) = \exp{(-\gamma \cdot \sum_{k=1}^{p}(x_{ik} - x_{jk})^2)}$

Instead, briefly when there are more than two classes (k > 2) there are two possible approches:

  • OVO (if k isn't too large): One - versus - One: Fit all $\binom{k}{2}$ pairwise classifiers. Classify $x^*$ to the class that "wins" the most pairwise competition;
  • OVA: One - versus - All: Fit K different 2-class SVM classifier; each class versus the rest. Classify $x^*$ to the class for which $f_k(x)$ is largest.

def my_SVM(dataset, y_class, kernel):
  # Split the dataset into train, validation and test set (5:2:3)
  x_train, x_test, y_train, y_test = train_test_split(dataset, y_class, test_size=0.3, random_state= None)
  x_train_complete = x_train # save the complete train set, before split in validation set
  y_train_complete = y_train
  # slit in validation and train sets, for further evaluation
  x_train, x_val, y_train, y_val = train_test_split(x_train, y_train, test_size=0.2, random_state= None)
  print("SVM with %s kernel" % kernel)

  print("Size train set: %d" % len(x_train))
  print("Size validation set: %d" % len(x_val))
  print("Size test set: %d" % len(x_test))

  #print(x_train.head())
  #print("\t|->Labels:" + str(y_train.head()))
  #print("\t|->Number of labels: %s" % str(y_train.value_counts()))
  #print("\nValidation set:")
  #print(x_val.head())
  #print("\t|->Labels:" + str(y_val.head()))
  #print("\t|->Number of labels: %s" % str(y_val.value_counts()))
  #print("\nTest set:")
  #print(x_test.head())
  #print("\t|->Labels:" + str(y_test.head()))
  #print("\t|->Number of labels: %s" % str(y_test.value_counts()))
  
  # Train and test, with validation set, for evaluating the C parameter from 10^-3 to 10^3
  c_min = 10**-3
  c_max = 10**3

  accuracies = []
  accuracy_max = 0  
  print("\nEvaluate SVM performace changing the C parameter")
  c = c_min
  while c <= c_max:
      print("\nTraining with C= %.3f" % c)
      classifier = svm.SVC(C = c, kernel = kernel, gamma= 'auto')
      classifier.fit(x_train, y_train) # train on train set
      print("\t|->End training\nTesting with validation set:")
      y_pred_val = classifier.predict(x_val) # evaluate on validation set
      accuracy = 100*f1_score(y_val, y_pred_val, average='binary')
      print("\t|->End testing - Accuracy= %.2f%%" % accuracy)
      accuracies.append(accuracy)
      if accuracy > accuracy_max:
          accuracy_max = accuracy
          best_c = c
      c *= 10

  for i in range(len(accuracies)):
      print("Accuracy %d : %.2f%%" % (i+1, accuracies[i]))
  print("Best C parameter is: %f with accuracy: %.2f%%" % (best_c, accuracy_max))

  # Now test the model with the test set and the best C found
  print("\nTraining with C= %.3f" % best_c)
  classifier = svm.SVC(C = best_c, kernel = kernel, gamma= 'auto')
  classifier.fit(x_train, y_train) # train on train set
  print("\t|->End training\nTesting with test set:")
  y_pred = classifier.predict(x_test) # evaluate on test set
  accuracy = 100*f1_score(y_test, y_pred, average='binary')
  print("\t|->End testing - Accuracy= %.2f%%" % accuracy) 
  
  print("Confusion matrix:")
  print(confusion_matrix(y_test, y_pred))
  print("Classification report")
  print(classification_report(y_test, y_pred))
 
  return accuracy
  
def my_SVM_with_GridSearch(dataset, y_class, kernel):
  # Grid Search with 5-fold validation
  x_train, x_test, y_train, y_test = train_test_split(dataset, y_class, test_size=0.3, random_state= None)
  
  svc = svm.SVC(kernel= kernel)
  parameters = {'C':[0.001, 0.01, 0.1, 1, 10, 100, 1000], 
                'gamma':[10**-11, 10**-9, 10**-7, 10**-5, 10**-3, 10**-1, 10]}
  classifier= GridSearchCV(svc, parameters, cv= 5, iid= False)
  print("SVM with %s kernel and GridSearch\nTraining..." % kernel)
  classifier.fit(x_train, y_train)
  print("End training, test:")
  y_pred = classifier.predict(x_test)
  best_c= classifier.best_params_['C']
  best_gamma= classifier.best_params_['gamma']
  best_accuracy= 100*classifier.best_score_
  print('Best parameters found in the Grid Search with 5-fold validation: ' + str(classifier.best_params_))
  print('Accuracy with these best parameters: %.2f' % best_accuracy + '%')

  # Evaluate score on the test set, with the best C and gamma values found
  accuracy = 100*f1_score(y_test, y_pred, average='binary')
  print('Accuracy on the test set with best parameters found %.2f%%' % accuracy)
  
  print("Confusion matrix:")
  print(confusion_matrix(y_test, y_pred))
  print("Classification report")
  print(classification_report(y_test, y_pred))
  classifier = svm.SVC(C = best_c, kernel = kernel, gamma=best_gamma)
  title = "Learning curve for SVM with " + kernel + " kernel and hyperparameters estimated with grid search"
  plot_learning_curve(classifier, title, x_train, y_train, cv=5)
  return accuracy

Start with defining our SVM functions.

There are two functions, which receive the dataset (samples and labels) and the desidered kernel.

In the first function, the dataset is splitted in three subsets:

  1. Train set: to train the classifier

  2. Validation set: to validate the parameters choosen

  3. Test set: to test the classifier and retrieve the final accuracy.

Here the parameter estimated to achieve the best accuracy is only C. In order to do this, a set of C values are tried, using the validation set, for the test phase. When the better C value is found by the given ones, the model is already trained and tested, but this time with the test set.

Instead, the second function perform the SVM, with the given dataset and kernel, but estimating the C and gamma values, by means of GridSearch and k-fold cross-validation. This time the dataset is splitted in train and test sets, due to the fact that, the cross-validation is used.

3.2 Decision Tree ¶

The decision tree is a supervised learning algorithm used both for regression and classification tasks.
It is based on a simple idea, for each feature in the dataset, it forms a node, using the most important attribute in the root node. So, it consists to recursive binary splitting, having a 'condition' or 'decision' that impose us if follow the left branch or the right one. The splitting continues until a leaf node is reached, which contains the outcome of the decision tree.
To perform the binary splits there are different measures useful to choose the best attribute for the node, for example the GINI index, or the entropy.

GINI index: measure of node impurity. Consider the node t:

$ GINI(t) = 1 - \sum_{j}[p(j|t)]^2 $

where, $p(j|t)$ is the relative frequency of class j at node t.
The GINI is maximum when all records are equally distribuited among all classes, this lead to an higher impurity degree; while, it is minimun (0), when all records belong the same class, producing lower impurity degree. Then, the quality of the split of the node p is computed as:
$ GINI_{split} = \sum_{i=1}^{k}\frac{n_i}{n} \cdot GINI(i)$

where:

  • $k$ is the number of partitions produced by the split;
  • $n_i$ is the number of records at child (partition) i;
  • $n$ is the number of records that arrives at node p.

Entropy: it is another measure, that works similar to the GINI index, write as:

$Entropy(t) = - \sum_{j}p(j|t)\cdot\log p(j|t)$

It is maximum ($\log n_c$) when all recorcords are equally distribuited among all classes, that leads an higher impurity degree; while is minimum (0) when all records belong the same class, lower impurity degree.
The quality of the split of parent node p is:
$ GAIN_{split} = Entropy(p) - \sum_{i=1}^{k}\frac{n_i}{n}\cdot Entropy(i)$

This classifier is extremely fast at classify unknown records, is easy to understand (graphically) and achieves accuracy similar to other classifier(e.g KNN) for simple dataset. The drawback is that it may be affected by missing data.
Obviously, also for this algorithm is important to handle two problems: underfitting (model too simple) and overfitting (model too fit to the dataset used to train, it recognizes very well that kind of data, but the error respect to completely new data, is very high).
To avoid the overfitting in the decision tree, there are two strategies:

  • Pre-pruning: stop the algorithm before it becomes a fully-grown tree, with more restrictive conditions, like stop the growing if the number of instances is less than some user-specified threshold;
  • Post-pruning: leave that the tree achieves its entirety dimension, so trim some node in a bottom-up fashion, and if the error improves after the trim, replace the sub-tree omitted by a leaf node.

Coming back to our case of study: start with defining our function, that performs the decision tree algorithm and plots it

In [0]:
def my_decisionTree(dataset, y_class, max_depth):
  x_train, x_test, y_train, y_test = train_test_split(dataset, y_class, test_size=0.3, random_state= None)
  print("\nTraining with maximum depth= %d" % max_depth)
  classifier = DecisionTreeClassifier(criterion="entropy", max_depth= max_depth)
  classifier.fit(x_train, y_train) # train on train set
  print("\t|->End training\nTesting with test set:")
  y_pred = classifier.predict(x_test) # evaluate on test set
  accuracy = 100*f1_score(y_test, y_pred, average='binary')
  print("\t|->End testing - Accuracy= %.2f%%" % accuracy)
  print("Confusion matrix:")
  print(confusion_matrix(y_test, y_pred))
  print("Classification report")
  print(classification_report(y_test, y_pred))
  
  # Visualize decision tree
  feature_cols = dataset.columns
  dot_data = StringIO()
  export_graphviz(classifier, out_file=dot_data,  
                  filled=True, rounded=True,
                  special_characters=True, feature_names = feature_cols,class_names=['0','1'])
  graph = pydotplus.graph_from_dot_data(dot_data.getvalue())  
  graph.write_png('decisionTree.png')
  Image(graph.create_png())
  
  plt.figure(figsize = (40, 32))
  plt.imshow(plt.imread('decisionTree.png'))
  plt.axis('off');
  plt.show();
  
  return accuracy

3.3 Random Forest¶

The random forest algorithm works building a set of decision tree and training them on a sub-set of records of dataset randomly picked. In the case of classification, the test sample is evaluated by each tree, so it is assigned to the category that wins the majority vote, between the outcomes produced by each 'internal' classifier.

The advantages of this algorithm are:

  • It is not biased, since there are multiple trees and each of them is tranied on a subset of samples;
  • Unlike decision tree, the random forest is not affected by missing data, and works well with categorical and numerical features

The disadvantages instead are:

  • Requires a lot of computational resouces, due to the high number of trees joined together;
  • For the previous reason, requires more time to train w.r.t. other comparable algorithms.

In our case, first of all, we define the function to compute the random forest algorithm.
The function my_randomForest receives the dataset, the labels and the number of estimators. If this one is 0, the function evaluates the performance of this classifier, among different n_estimators values. For this purpose, the dataset is split in train, test and validation set. The mechanisms is the same explained for the SVM.
Otherwise the number of trees specified by the user is used. In this case the dataset is split only in train and test sets, the classifier is trained with the train set and then tested with the other set.
The function returns also in this case, the accuracy achieved, and show some results, like the confusion matrix and the classification report.

In [0]:
def my_randomForest(dataset, y_class, n_estimators):
  # Split the dataset into train, validation and test set (5:2:3)
  x_train, x_test, y_train, y_test = train_test_split(dataset, y_class, test_size=0.3, random_state= None)
  x_train_complete = x_train # save the complete train set, before split in validation set
  y_train_complete = y_train
  # slit in validation and train sets, for further evaluation
  x_train, x_val, y_train, y_val = train_test_split(x_train, y_train, test_size=0.2, random_state= None)
  
  # evaluate the best number of trees needed if the parameter received is 0
  if n_estimators == 0:
    number_of_trees = [10, 20, 50, 100, 1000]
    best_accuracy = 0
    for trees in number_of_trees:
      print("\nTraining random forest classifier with n_estimators= %d" % trees)
      classifier = RandomForestClassifier(n_estimators=trees, criterion="entropy")
      classifier.fit(x_train, y_train) # train on train set
      print("\t|->End training\nTesting with validation set:")
      y_pred = classifier.predict(x_val) # evaluate on validation set
      accuracy = 100*f1_score(y_val, y_pred, average='binary')
      print("\t|->End testing - Accuracy= %.2f%%" % accuracy)
      
      if accuracy > best_accuracy:
        best_accuracy = accuracy
        n_estimators = trees
    print("\nBest number of trees evaluated: %d" % n_estimators)
    print("---------------------------------------------------------")
    print("\nTraining random forest classifier with the best number of estimators evaluated")
    
  else: 
    print("\nTraining random forest classifier with n_estimators= %d" % n_estimators)
  classifier = RandomForestClassifier(n_estimators=n_estimators, criterion="entropy")
  classifier.fit(x_train_complete, y_train_complete) # train on train set
  print("\t|->End training\nTesting with test set:")
  
  y_pred = classifier.predict(x_test) # evaluate on test set
  accuracy = 100*f1_score(y_test, y_pred, average='binary')
  print("\t|->End testing - Accuracy= %.2f%%" % accuracy)
  print("Confusion matrix:")
  print(confusion_matrix(y_test, y_pred))
  print("Classification report")
  print(classification_report(y_test, y_pred))

  return accuracy

3.4 KNN ¶

The K-Nearest Neighbors algorithm (KNN) is a non-parametric method, which considers the K closest training examples to the point of interest for predicting its class. This is done by a simple majority vote over the K closest points. The distance metric could be chosen from a set of possibilities, for example is common to use the Euclidean distance for continuos samples, while the Hamming distance for discrete ones.

First of all, define our KNN function, that receives the dataset, samples and labels. This function splits the dataset in train and test sets. It receives also a third parameter, for the K value:

  • if it is 0, the function searches the best k, that provides the lowest mean error, and finally train and test again the classifier, with the best K value found, evaluating the performances.
  • otherwise, train and test the classifier with the received K value.
In [0]:
def my_KNN(dataset, y_class, k):
  # Split the dataset in train an test set
  X_train, X_test, y_train, y_test = train_test_split(dataset, y_class, test_size=0.20)
  
  if k == 0:
    min_error= math.inf
    best_k = 0
    errors = []
    print("Evaluate K in [1,40]... please wait!")
    # Calculating error for K values between 1 and 10 searching the best K value
    for i in range(1, 40):  
      #print("Evaluate KNN with K= %d" % i)
      knn = KNeighborsClassifier(n_neighbors=i)
      knn.fit(X_train, y_train)
      pred_i = knn.predict(X_test)
      error = np.mean(pred_i != y_test)
      #print("\t|->Error= %.2f" % error)
      errors.append(error)
      if error < min_error:
        min_error = error
        best_k = i

    print("Best K= %d" % best_k)
  
    # Plot the error trend
    fig, ax = plt.subplots()
    ax.grid()
    fig.figsize=(12, 6)
    ax.plot(range(1, 40), errors, color='red', linestyle='dashed', marker='o',  
             markerfacecolor='blue', markersize=10)
    ax.set(xlabel='K Value', ylabel='Mean Error', title='Error Rate K Value')
    plt.show()
    plt.clf()
  
  else:
    best_k = k
    
  # Perform the KNN with the best k and evaluate the results
  classifier = KNeighborsClassifier(n_neighbors=best_k)  
  
  # Train the model with the train set
  print("Train the model with K= %d" % best_k)
  classifier.fit(X_train, y_train)
  
  # Test the model with the test set
  print("Evaluate the model:")
  y_pred = classifier.predict(X_test)
  
  # Print result of classification
  #print(y_pred)
  print("Confusion matrix:")
  print(confusion_matrix(y_test, y_pred))  
  print("Classification report")
  print(classification_report(y_test, y_pred))
  
  accuracy = 100*f1_score(y_test, y_pred, average='binary')
  print("Accuracy: %.2f%%" % accuracy)
  
  classifier = KNeighborsClassifier(n_neighbors=best_k) 
  title = "Learning curve for KNN with K= " + str(best_k)
  plot_learning_curve(classifier, title, X_train, y_train, cv=5)
  return accuracy

4. Regression ¶

4.1 Linear regression ¶

Linear regression is one of the most famous technique for value prediction. Differently from the classification it is used to predict real values. It is based on the assumption that there exists a linear relationship between a variable $\textit{Y}$ and a set of predictors $\textit{X}_1, \textit{X}_2, \dots, \textit{X}_p$ and it tries to model the relationship by means of this linearity, such that:

$\hat{Y} = \beta_0+\beta_1X_1+\beta_2X_2+\dots+\beta_pX_p + \varepsilon$

The values of the coefficient $\beta_j$ are choosen in a way that they minimizes the $\textit{RSS}$ ($\textit{residual sum of squares}$).

$RSS = \sum_{i=1}^{n}(y_i-\hat{y}_i)^2$

$\varepsilon$ is the error term which is a catch-all for what we miss with this simple model (non-linearity, measuring error, missing samples, missing variables..). In general we consider that $\varepsilon$ is independent of $\textit{X}$

The dataset prepared for the regression consists in 6 different features listed below.

F-statistic¶

Another way to understand which are the most important predictors is to test the null hypothesis $\textit{H}_0$. We can define two main hypothesis, the null and its alternative:

$H_0 : \beta_1 = \beta_2 = \beta_3 = \dots = \beta_p = 0$
$H_a$: at least one $\beta_j$ is different from $0$

For what concern the simple linear regression the $\textit{H}_0$ verification is simpler and consists in estimate $\hat{\beta_1}$ in such a way it can guarantee that $\beta_1 \neq 0$. In this scenario the $\textit{t-statistic}$ measures the number of standard deviation that $\beta_1 \neq 0$.

$t=\frac{\hat{\beta}_1-0}{SE{\hat{\beta}_1}}$

where:

$SE({\hat{\beta}_1})^2=\frac{\sigma^2}{\sum_{i=1}^{n}(x_i-\overline{x})^2}, \sigma^2 = Var(\beta_1)$

The multiple linear regression instead require the definition of $\textit{F-statistic}$. The $\textit{F-statistic}$ is used to understand when $\textit{Y}$ is related with $\textit{X}$. The null hypothesis is performed by computing this statistic which have the following form:

$F=\frac{\frac{TSS - RSS}{p}}{\frac{RSS}{n-p-1}}$

When there is no relationship between response and predictors $F \approx 1$, else if $\textit{H}_a$ is true then $F > 1$.
Another important indicator is the $\textit{p-value}$ associated with each predictors. This indicator can be seen as the probability of that predictor to be zero (thus verifying the $\textit{H}_0$ hypothesis), so higher is the value, smaller is the statistic meaning of this predictors. Tipically a predictors can be omitted from the analysis if its $\textit{p-value}$ is higher than a certa threshold $\alpha$ (e.g. $\alpha = 0.05$)

y = np.log(y_regr)

Accuracy¶

The accuracy of regression model should be an indicator of how good the model fits the data. There are two main ways for evaluating the accuracy of a regression model:

* Residual standard error (RSE)
* R-squared

The RSE is an estimate of the standard deviation of $\varepsilon$, so it is the average amount that the response will deviate from the true regression line. A good model should have a RSE that tends to be 0.

$RSE = \sqrt{\frac{1}{n-2}RSS} = \sqrt{\frac{1}{n-2}\sum_{i=1}^{n}(y_i - \hat{y}_i)^2}$

Because of the RSE is measured in the units of $\textit{Y}$ it is not always clear what constitutes a good value for the RSE.
The $\textit{R-squared}$ provides an alternative statistic and it takes the form of a proportion of the variance explained, so independent of the scale of $\textit{Y}$.

$R^2 = \frac{TSS-RSS}{TSS} = 1 - \frac{RSS}{TSS}$

where

$TSS = \sum_{i=1}^{n}(y_i - \overline{y}_i)^2$

$\textit{TSS}$: amount of variability inherent in the response before the regression is applied.
$\textit{RSS}$: amount of variability that is left unexplained after performing the regression.
$\textit{TSS-RSS}$: amount of variability in the response that is explained by performing the regression.

So the $\textit{R-squared}$ measures the proportion of variability in $\textit{Y}$ that can be explained using $\textit{Y}$. It is a value $\epsilon$ $[0, 1]$ where a low $\textit{R-squared}$ means a wrong model or a high error (or both).

4.2 Regression tree ¶

Another important technique to perform regression is to use tree-based methods. These methods provide great explainability but generally worse accuracy than other supervised algorithms.
The main idea is to divide the feature space composed by $X_1,X_2,\dots,X_j$ in $J$ different and non overlapping sub-regions $R_1,R_2,\dots,R_j$. This procedure creates a tree which, starting from the root, expands in different branches representing the cutting-point for the sub-regions up to the final leaves that represents each single sub-region $R_i$. For every observation that falls inside sub-region $R_i$, the response will be the average of all the responses of each training observation that fell inside the region.

How to find the regions $R_1,R_2,\dots,R_j$ ?
Let's find $J$ regions that minimizes the $RSS$:

$RSS = \sum_{j=1}^{J}\sum_{i\epsilon R_j}(y_i - \hat{y}_{R_j})^2$

The problem of finding all the possible $J$ partition of the feature space that minimizes the $RSS$ is unfeasible, so a top-down greedy approach called $\textit{recursive binary splitting}$ has to be used. The approach is greedy because we decide each cutting point withouth taking in consideration future steps and top-down because we start from the root of the tree. At first step we choose among $p$ feature predictors and cutting point for each features, the predictor $X_i$ and the cutting point $s$ so that splitting the predictor space into regions $\{X|X_j<s\}$ and $\{X|X_j\geqslant s\}$ lead to the greates possible reduction in $RSS$.
Writing down some equations we search the subspaces $R_1$ and $R_2$ in such a way they minimize the $RSS$:

$R_1(j,s)=\{X|X_j

$\sum_{i:x_i\epsilon R_1(j,s)}(y_i-\hat{y}_{R_1})^2+\sum_{i:x_i\epsilon R_2(j,s)}(y_i-\hat{y}_{R_2})^2$

Where the values $\hat{y}_{R_1}$ and $\hat{y}_{R_2}$ are the mean responses for the training observation respectively in $R_1$ and $R_2$. In next step we choose the predictors not among all the initial features but among $p-1$ features. We continue this process until a stopping criterion is reached, for instance when each subspace contains no more than $k$ examples.

Tree pruning:¶

The $\textit{recursive binary splitting}$ often lead to very complex tree that overfits the training data. In order to avoid that we should take in consideration a smaller tree by means of a pruning technique. We will describe in this section the $\textit{cost complexity pruning}$.
Cost complexity pruning consists in choosing a sequence of trees from the original one, each one indexed by a nonnegative tuning parameter $\alpha$. We perform cross validation to choose the best value of $\alpha$ and then choose the correspondent pruned tree. For each value of $\alpha$ we search for the tree that minizes the following equation:

$\sum_{m=1}^{\|T\|}\sum_{i:x_i\epsilon R_m}(y_i-\hat{y}_{R_m})^2+\alpha \|T\|$

Where $\|T\|$ is the number of terminal nodes of the tree.
The above equation is a trade off between the tree complexity and its fit to the training data. When $\alpha$ is high we penalize more the complex trees, but we always take care about the $RSS$ of the tree. With cross-validation we can tune $\alpha$ and return the tree that minimizes the above quantity.

4.3 Random forests regression ¶

The $R^2$ scores for the decision tree regressor above were very poor. Another possibility is to build more than one single tree and then take as response the average of responses for each tree.
$\textit{Bagging}$ consists in build different trees and fit each of them onto a set of data created by bootstrapping the training set. We then train $B$ different regressor trees and take as response the average response of trees, in this way we reduce the variance.

$\hat{f}_{avg}(x) = \frac{1}{B}\sum_{b=1}^{B}\hat{f}^b(x)$

$\textit{Random forests}$ is instead a technique which also try to decorrelates the builded trees. The main idea is that each tree of a bagging will have some strong predictors and other weak ones, so each tree will take as first split always the stronger ones, make them correlated to each others. In order to avoid that, $\textit{Random forests}$ decide at each step among $m$ out of $p$ randomly selected predictors for the split, tipically $m=\sqrt{p}$.
Here below we have applied $\textit{Random forests}$ with 1000 and 100 different trees an it can be noticed how $R^2$ scores are slightly better with the respect to both single regressor tree and linear regression, even if they still miss some important predictors.

Conclusions:¶

We have performed regression on the Berlin-Airbnb dataset in order to predict the price of each ads on the listings. The most powerful technique we have found for such a task was the $\textit{Random forests}$ with 1000 different trees.
Regarding the regression, unfortunately results were very poor but we do not think that our model was wrong. What we think is that the price of the house is for sure related with the district and the type of room but, some important missing features, such as the house size, the furniture, the presence of a balcony or a garden are the main discriminants to predict the price of a house. For this reason we conclude our prediction analysis asserting that this type of dataset is not so useful for such a task.

5. Final considerations ¶

We have performed classification and regression on the Berlin AirBnb dataset of 2018. The results are quite good for the classification task whose goal is to predict the correct type of room given the other features.
The regression instead aims to predict the price of the house given other features like neighbourhood and type of room. In this work the results are quite bad but we are conscious that the dataset is not ideal for this type of task as we have already assert.
